<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-569-221  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 569 221.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE on andamp; about ATandamp;T  Oct 29, 1990 v5 n118 p2(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MCI: forms strategic marketing alliance with Comdisco. Up to 300T1's by 1995.(MCI Communications Corp., Comdisco Disaster RecoveryServices Inc.)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (Contracts)Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services Inc. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     Marketing AgreementsT1 CommunicationsDisaster RecoverySupport ServicesNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MCI Communications Corp. and Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services Inc. (CDRS)have formed a strategic marketing alliance to address companies' criticaldata recovery needs.andM;The marketing alliance will permit customers to obtain a combination of MCI'sdata communications services and CDRS' business continuity services.andM;MCI and CDRS will work together in providing business customers withemergency-type data recovery needs.andP;  For customers seeking continuity of dataand essential business services during times of disaster, the two companieswill cooperate to design and install customized network rerouting solutions.andM;In addition, MCI will design and implement a data network to support CDRS'backbone network which is an integral part of CDRS' new deliveryarchitecture, CDRS Net.andM;&quot;MCI will be providing this alliance with a network comprised of diverselyrouted and redundant transmission facilities, including TDS 1.5, TDS 45, andDigital Private Line circuits.andP;  We are exploring the possibility of expandingthis alliance globally as our next phase.&quot; said Don Heath, MCI's VicePresident of Data Marketing.andM;&quot;This alliance is strategic to CDRS,&quot; said Ray Hipp, president of CDRS.andP;  &quot;TheMCI data network will be the basis of our CDRS Net architecture and positionsus to be able to provide our business continuity subscribers with acost-effective and reliable solution to the complex issues of networkrecovery and electronic data movement.&quot;andM;CDRS Net is an architecture that involves the integration of BusinessRecovery Facilities (BRFs) and Computer Recovery Facilities (CRFs) through ahigh speed backbone network comprised of 80 T-1s at full implementation(summer 1991).andM;&quot;Through CDRS' Network Services Gateways that are primarily located atstrategic fiber hubs, and MCI Central offices, we are able to offersubscribers convenient yet cost-effective data circuits that access not onlyour BRFs and CRFs, but also our full line of Continuous Availability Servicesincluding Remote Journaling, Electronic Vaulting and Data Base Shadowing,&quot;continued Hipp.andP;  &quot;The full implementation of this service will include anetwork of up to 300 T-1s by 1995.&quot;andM;Founded in 1980, CDRS is the world's leading provider of business continuityservices.andP;  It provides a network of fully equipped computer centers which areavailable in the event of fire, flood, power outage or any other disasteraffecting a customer's data center.andP;  In addition to its network of nine NorthAmerica recovery centers, CDRS is affiliated with Comdisco Disaster RecoveryServices Canada Ltd., Failsafe ROC Ltd., located in the United Kingdom, andAgeris International in Paris, as well as joint venture recovery facilitiesin Singapore and Malaysia.andM;MCI had 1989 revenue of approximately $6.5 billion.andO;</TEXT></DOC>